WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:12.795
GREG HARTRELL: So today, I have
the privilege of welcoming you

00:00:12.795 --> 00:00:14.677
to Google's Developer Day 2015.

00:00:14.677 --> 00:00:17.260
I want to spend a little bit of
time talking about how we view

00:00:17.260 --> 00:00:20.120
the opportunity in mobile
games with all of our platforms

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:22.000
and services, and then
take you through some

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:24.458
of the new announcements that
we're really excited to share

00:00:24.458 --> 00:00:25.110
with you today.

00:00:25.110 --> 00:00:28.090
As you all know, Android
is incredibly popular.

00:00:28.090 --> 00:00:30.550
And the platform has
grown tremendously

00:00:30.550 --> 00:00:33.530
since we launched it
in 2008 with the G1

00:00:33.530 --> 00:00:35.830
to a mere few thousand users.

00:00:35.830 --> 00:00:39.480
Six short years later, it's the
most popular mobile operating

00:00:39.480 --> 00:00:42.030
system platform in the
world, accounting for three

00:00:42.030 --> 00:00:45.070
out of every four smartphones
and three out of every five

00:00:45.070 --> 00:00:47.570
tablets.

00:00:47.570 --> 00:00:49.940
And Android's not
only popular, but it's

00:00:49.940 --> 00:00:52.420
amazing to see how powerful
the platform's become.

00:00:52.420 --> 00:00:56.060
And we know that more than
85% of Android devices

00:00:56.060 --> 00:00:58.570
are now running
Android 4.0 and higher,

00:00:58.570 --> 00:01:01.602
and that's growing every day.

00:01:01.602 --> 00:01:03.310
But if you look beyond
just market share,

00:01:03.310 --> 00:01:06.000
the aggregate size of
the Android device base

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:07.800
is equally impressive.

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:10.280
It's grown exponentially
over the last few years,

00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:12.140
and its velocity continues.

00:01:12.140 --> 00:01:14.500
We crossed this
milestone last year,

00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:17.000
announcing that we have over
a billion active devices

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:18.280
around the world.

00:01:18.280 --> 00:01:21.970
That scale is truly
unprecedented.

00:01:21.970 --> 00:01:25.370
And when you take a
games lens to this,

00:01:25.370 --> 00:01:27.560
there's three in
four Android users

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:29.800
playing games from Google Play.

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:32.290
That is a lot of people
playing games, needless to say.

00:01:32.290 --> 00:01:34.459
And this kind of
audience makes Google

00:01:34.459 --> 00:01:36.750
Play one of the most interesting
opportunities for game

00:01:36.750 --> 00:01:39.220
developers today.

00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:41.450
Android is also a
truly global platform.

00:01:41.450 --> 00:01:43.260
And judging from
the audience, we

00:01:43.260 --> 00:01:45.650
know that you're coming from
all corners of the globe,

00:01:45.650 --> 00:01:47.720
and the scale of our
international growth

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:49.190
is pretty amazing.

00:01:49.190 --> 00:01:53.672
We have partnerships with 60
device manufacturers, devices

00:01:53.672 --> 00:01:55.130
all over the world
that are running

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:58.510
on 329 distinct carriers.

00:01:58.510 --> 00:02:03.390
And the people using Android
come from over 190 countries.

00:02:03.390 --> 00:02:05.210
When you combine
all that together,

00:02:05.210 --> 00:02:07.510
this might be the largest
platform of people playing

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:10.940
games perhaps ever created,
and our investments here

00:02:10.940 --> 00:02:12.992
are going to continue.

00:02:12.992 --> 00:02:14.700
One of the areas that
we invest in really

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:17.210
heavily is also in our global
payments infrastructure.

00:02:17.210 --> 00:02:20.830
In the past few years, we've
done great integrations

00:02:20.830 --> 00:02:22.290
with carriers for billing.

00:02:22.290 --> 00:02:25.310
We're doing that now in 32
countries around the world.

00:02:25.310 --> 00:02:27.820
We've accelerated the rollout
of Google Play gift cards

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:31.330
in retail locations, and we
have that now in 28 countries.

00:02:31.330 --> 00:02:35.920
And PayPal is a form of
payment in 19 countries

00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:38.550
and going strong.

00:02:38.550 --> 00:02:41.620
I'm also happy to say that
with this growth of Android

00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:44.640
and Google Play, it's paying
off for developers too.

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:46.640
Last week, we announced
that Google Play

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:50.740
has paid out over $7 billion to
developers over the past year.

00:02:50.740 --> 00:02:53.390
And that makes the
opportunity for apps and games

00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:55.190
really intense.

00:02:55.190 --> 00:02:57.020
And so starting from
phones and tablets,

00:02:57.020 --> 00:03:01.750
and going to TVs, wearables,
and cars, Android is expanding.

00:03:01.750 --> 00:03:04.660
And while Android and Play
are these platforms that

00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:06.400
make these devices
possible, the truth

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:08.479
is the games that you
create, and the apps that

00:03:08.479 --> 00:03:10.020
are brought to the
ecosystem, is what

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:12.020
makes them really worthwhile.

00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:13.520
And so that's one
of the reasons why

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:16.130
we're big on helping you
tap into this opportunity.

00:03:16.130 --> 00:03:18.500
Google helps take your
games to new heights

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:21.680
through our strengths in
mobile and in cloud services.

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:24.490
This collection of
platforms and services

00:03:24.490 --> 00:03:26.310
help you distribute
to a mass audience,

00:03:26.310 --> 00:03:30.170
promote and monetize your
game, and build your audience,

00:03:30.170 --> 00:03:33.190
and measure your success.

00:03:33.190 --> 00:03:34.932
So that's the opportunity
in a nutshell.

00:03:34.932 --> 00:03:37.140
What I want to do is switch
to talking the new stuff,

00:03:37.140 --> 00:03:39.223
and this can be thought
of in these three buckets.

00:03:39.223 --> 00:03:42.986
We'll talk about new things to
measure and monetize your game.

00:03:42.986 --> 00:03:44.360
We'll talk about
the living room,

00:03:44.360 --> 00:03:46.234
and then we'll talk
about completely new game

00:03:46.234 --> 00:03:48.820
experiences that are emerging.

00:03:48.820 --> 00:03:51.560
So on the measurement front,
when you publish your game

00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:54.910
through Google Play,
you get really key tools

00:03:54.910 --> 00:03:57.442
from Google Play services
and the Google Play Developer

00:03:57.442 --> 00:03:58.661
Console.

00:03:58.661 --> 00:04:00.660
These are essential to
running an effective game

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:02.397
business in our ecosystem.

00:04:02.397 --> 00:04:04.480
Some recent announcements
in the Developer Console

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:06.997
involve our conversion
rate reports.

00:04:06.997 --> 00:04:08.455
This is the percentage
of users who

00:04:08.455 --> 00:04:10.788
have purchased an in-app item
or subscription since they

00:04:10.788 --> 00:04:13.195
installed the game, and our
spending per buyer report,

00:04:13.195 --> 00:04:14.820
which shows your
users and what they've

00:04:14.820 --> 00:04:17.154
spent cumulatively since they
made their first purchase.

00:04:17.154 --> 00:04:19.778
Of course, it's really essential
when you're updating your game

00:04:19.778 --> 00:04:22.140
to understand how player
spending behaviors are changing

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:25.450
over time and understanding
whether their lifetime value is

00:04:25.450 --> 00:04:27.480
working out the way
that you expect.

00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:30.090
We also announced the ability
to programmatically access Play

00:04:30.090 --> 00:04:30.590
data.

00:04:30.590 --> 00:04:31.865
So if you have
internal tools where

00:04:31.865 --> 00:04:34.160
you want to bring in this
data and analyze it yourself,

00:04:34.160 --> 00:04:36.800
or use it in third party
tools, or other query

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:39.610
engines like Google's BigQuery,
that's available to you

00:04:39.610 --> 00:04:41.570
now as well.

00:04:41.570 --> 00:04:44.650
In past announcements,
we've talked to you

00:04:44.650 --> 00:04:46.400
about Google Play
Games, our game network,

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:50.100
which continues to grow and help
developers engage and retain

00:04:50.100 --> 00:04:51.220
their users.

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:52.840
It is growing at a
rapid pace, and we

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:55.260
see more and more developers
incorporating it and seeing

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:56.650
great results.

00:04:56.650 --> 00:04:58.910
If you have exemplary
implementations for things

00:04:58.910 --> 00:05:01.630
like achievements,
leaderboards, quests,

00:05:01.630 --> 00:05:03.910
we're finding developers
able to substantially retain

00:05:03.910 --> 00:05:06.210
their users, increase
their lifetime value

00:05:06.210 --> 00:05:08.555
and their revenue as a result.

00:05:08.555 --> 00:05:10.680
Now, last year, we talked
to you about bringing you

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:13.160
demographic data and
key business metrics

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:15.090
through the Google
Play Developer Console,

00:05:15.090 --> 00:05:17.290
if you've incorporated
game services.

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:19.650
And after experiencing
the benefits of that data,

00:05:19.650 --> 00:05:21.360
many of you are
actively using it

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:22.830
but also told you
you wanted more.

00:05:22.830 --> 00:05:24.788
You wanted more player
insights, and you wanted

00:05:24.788 --> 00:05:25.949
more key business metrics.

00:05:25.949 --> 00:05:28.240
So we've heard you, and I'd
like to invite my colleague

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:30.760
Ben onto the stage to tell
you about a new feature

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:33.500
that we call Play Games
Play Analytics that's

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:34.730
launching soon.

00:05:34.730 --> 00:05:36.024
Ben.

00:05:36.024 --> 00:05:38.510
BEN FRENKEL: Which one of these
buttons is the [? board? ?]

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:39.300
GREG HARTRELL: You go right.

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:39.730
BEN FRENKEL: Right.

00:05:39.730 --> 00:05:41.230
GREG HARTRELL: And the center
button's the laser pointer.

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:42.410
Essential.

00:05:42.410 --> 00:05:44.960
BEN FRENKEL: Center button,
laser pointer-- check.

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:46.250
All right.

00:05:46.250 --> 00:05:48.050
I think we're all set.

00:05:48.050 --> 00:05:50.204
So thank you, Greg.

00:05:50.204 --> 00:05:51.620
Creating a great
game is no longer

00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:54.200
enough to be successful
in mobile gaming.

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:57.670
It's still required, but it's
now an insufficient condition

00:05:57.670 --> 00:05:58.710
for success.

00:05:58.710 --> 00:06:00.970
And as we look at the
mobile gaming landscape,

00:06:00.970 --> 00:06:03.690
it's increasingly
split into two camps--

00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:05.440
those with the
resources and tools

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:10.000
to manage their game as a
service, and everyone else.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.490
And when we look at larger
developers that successfully

00:06:12.490 --> 00:06:14.260
manage their game
as a service, we

00:06:14.260 --> 00:06:17.580
find that they do three
things really well.

00:06:17.580 --> 00:06:20.720
One, they set and
manage their business

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:22.430
to daily revenue targets.

00:06:22.430 --> 00:06:26.540
Two, they can identify hotspots
in their business metrics

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:28.970
so they can continuously
focus on the updates

00:06:28.970 --> 00:06:31.150
to their game that will
have the most impact.

00:06:31.150 --> 00:06:33.930
And three, they use
analytics to understand

00:06:33.930 --> 00:06:37.100
how their players are
progressing, spending,

00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:39.040
and churning.

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:41.950
So what does it take
for a typical big studio

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:44.280
to do all these things?

00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:47.610
Well, a big studio
will have many teams

00:06:47.610 --> 00:06:50.820
managing all the different
functions of a game studio.

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:53.590
So you'll have a team of people
focused on game development,

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:56.740
obviously, a group of
data scientists focused

00:06:56.740 --> 00:07:00.680
on analytics, and teams for
operations, and infrastructure

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:04.580
support, and
marketing, and so on.

00:07:04.580 --> 00:07:08.960
On the other hand, this is
what you, the indie developer,

00:07:08.960 --> 00:07:13.110
probably looks like-- a
small team, possibly just one

00:07:13.110 --> 00:07:15.950
developer, doing everything.

00:07:15.950 --> 00:07:17.910
Now, this indie developer
here, this happy guy

00:07:17.910 --> 00:07:21.160
with the green hoodie, he
wants to spend all of his time

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:23.490
focused on building
games, right?

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:26.050
I'm sure many of you in the
audience feel the same way.

00:07:26.050 --> 00:07:27.359
And you know what?

00:07:27.359 --> 00:07:29.400
That leaves very little
time for everything else.

00:07:29.400 --> 00:07:33.280
And it's bridging
this gap between what

00:07:33.280 --> 00:07:37.160
the big studios can do and
what you, the indie developer,

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:40.910
can do that was the
primary motivation for what

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:44.720
we're excited to announce
today-- Play Games Player

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:45.780
Analytics.

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:48.440
So its launching in the next
few weeks, in the Play Developer

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:51.030
Console, and this
new tool will enable

00:07:51.030 --> 00:07:52.530
you to do the
three things I just

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:57.420
described-- manage your business
to daily revenue targets,

00:07:57.420 --> 00:07:59.660
identify hotspots in
your business metrics

00:07:59.660 --> 00:08:02.150
so you can continuously
focus on the updates

00:08:02.150 --> 00:08:05.230
to your game that will have
the most impact, and three,

00:08:05.230 --> 00:08:08.550
understand how your players
are progressing, spending,

00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:09.320
and churning.

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:13.390
And all of Player Analytics
is available for free

00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:16.280
in the Developer Console
for everybody who

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:18.490
integrates Play game services.

00:08:18.490 --> 00:08:20.860
So I'll quickly walk you
through the set of experiences

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:23.090
we'll be providing at launch.

00:08:23.090 --> 00:08:27.080
So everything starts with you
setting your daily revenue

00:08:27.080 --> 00:08:28.440
targets.

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:31.110
And from there, once
you've done that,

00:08:31.110 --> 00:08:34.260
you can come back into the
Developer Console every day

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:37.409
and check to see if you're on
track to meet your business

00:08:37.409 --> 00:08:38.360
objectives.

00:08:38.360 --> 00:08:40.070
And as you can see
in the chart here,

00:08:40.070 --> 00:08:44.630
this developer has set their
daily revenue target to $125,

00:08:44.630 --> 00:08:47.770
is on track to exceed
their monthly goal,

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:48.520
and you know what?

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:50.395
At the end of the month,
they should probably

00:08:50.395 --> 00:08:52.460
consider raising
their target higher.

00:08:52.460 --> 00:08:56.200
But if it wasn't a
positive trend in the data

00:08:56.200 --> 00:09:00.640
that they were seeing, and
they were below the line, then

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:03.220
this report would end up
being the starting point

00:09:03.220 --> 00:09:07.020
of an investigation into how
they can improve their game.

00:09:07.020 --> 00:09:09.610
And to help you
focus on the areas

00:09:09.610 --> 00:09:12.330
where your game updates
will have the most impact,

00:09:12.330 --> 00:09:14.890
we give you the ability
to identify hotspots

00:09:14.890 --> 00:09:16.640
in your business metrics.

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:19.190
So first, we compute
a set of benchmarks

00:09:19.190 --> 00:09:22.140
from a variety of inputs,
including the category

00:09:22.140 --> 00:09:23.630
that your game is in.

00:09:23.630 --> 00:09:25.870
And based on those
benchmarks, we

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:29.880
create a heat map of your
key financial and engagement

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:32.100
metrics.

00:09:32.100 --> 00:09:36.360
Metrics highlighted in red
are likely to offer the best

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:37.889
opportunity for improvement.

00:09:37.889 --> 00:09:39.722
And as you can see here,
this game developer

00:09:39.722 --> 00:09:41.590
is doing pretty well overall.

00:09:41.590 --> 00:09:45.360
See that sea of green there
in the chart at the bottom?

00:09:45.360 --> 00:09:46.940
Green is good.

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:49.930
And so there's one exception.

00:09:49.930 --> 00:09:52.400
Average revenue per
user is in dark red,

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:55.480
and trending down, and
well below the benchmark

00:09:55.480 --> 00:09:56.790
for similar games.

00:09:56.790 --> 00:10:00.420
And this developer can
now have a laser focus

00:10:00.420 --> 00:10:02.850
on improving just one
thing now, and that's

00:10:02.850 --> 00:10:05.125
average revenue per user.

00:10:05.125 --> 00:10:06.500
And to help you
better understand

00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:08.440
how your players are
progressing, spending,

00:10:08.440 --> 00:10:11.410
and churning, we give you
this classic retention table

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:15.140
and player progression
funnel, as you can see here.

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:18.230
Now, everything I just
described is available to you

00:10:18.230 --> 00:10:22.180
by virtue of your integration
with Play game services

00:10:22.180 --> 00:10:25.520
with near zero
incremental effort.

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:28.030
But for a little
extra work, you'll

00:10:28.030 --> 00:10:30.940
be able to unlock another
set of valuable reports

00:10:30.940 --> 00:10:32.410
with the Sources
and Sinks Report,

00:10:32.410 --> 00:10:35.632
which I'll go over in
a second, starting off.

00:10:35.632 --> 00:10:37.590
Throughout the development
of Player Analytics,

00:10:37.590 --> 00:10:40.830
we have been fortunate to work
with some amazing partners,

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:43.130
and one of them is
in the room today.

00:10:43.130 --> 00:10:44.550
And I can see him right there.

00:10:44.550 --> 00:10:47.270
It's Eric Froemling, the
developer of "BombSquad."

00:10:47.270 --> 00:10:49.400
Let's go ahead and
wave to the crowd here.

00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:51.670
You're going to want to
talk to him after this

00:10:51.670 --> 00:10:53.910
and learn a little bit
more about his experiences

00:10:53.910 --> 00:10:56.720
with Player Analytics.

00:10:56.720 --> 00:11:00.230
So Eric is the archetype
of that indie developer

00:11:00.230 --> 00:11:04.670
that I was describing before
but without the green hoodie.

00:11:04.670 --> 00:11:07.070
And he's a one-man army
that does everything

00:11:07.070 --> 00:11:08.680
for his critically
acclaimed game,

00:11:08.680 --> 00:11:11.570
"BombSquad," including having
built the underlying game

00:11:11.570 --> 00:11:13.755
engine, which is
extremely impressive.

00:11:13.755 --> 00:11:16.620
And when we started working
with Eric a month or so ago,

00:11:16.620 --> 00:11:19.850
we could tell Eric had a
great game on his hands--

00:11:19.850 --> 00:11:24.340
millions of downloads, engaged
users, a loyal fan base.

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:25.960
But like many of
you in the audience

00:11:25.960 --> 00:11:30.640
who also have a great game, he
was struggling to make money.

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:33.960
So when Eric started to dig
into the Player Analytics data,

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:37.350
in particular the Sources and
Sinks Report you can see here,

00:11:37.350 --> 00:11:42.370
he was immediately able to spot
an imbalance in "BombSquad's"

00:11:42.370 --> 00:11:43.550
game economy.

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:45.780
He was giving away tickets,
his premium currency,

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:48.900
at a higher rate than people
were able to spend them.

