00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:05.260
Because it's stock Android,
using the same services as

00:19:05.260 --> 00:19:08.220
mobile and tablet, you're going
to be able to bring all of that

00:19:08.220 --> 00:19:12.060
over with a lean back experience
and get the same APIs.

00:19:12.060 --> 00:19:14.800
The Play Store continues
to be the distribution

00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:15.580
point of record.

00:19:15.580 --> 00:19:17.700
So you have a familiar
distribution and promotion

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:20.300
capability there, with all of
the functionality that you've

00:19:20.300 --> 00:19:21.970
come to expect from us.

00:19:21.970 --> 00:19:23.830
And lastly, from a
standards point of view,

00:19:23.830 --> 00:19:27.180
we have user experience
guidelines for apps and games,

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:30.450
to develop a higher
quality ecosystem, but also

00:19:30.450 --> 00:19:33.860
hardware accessory standards
for accessories like gamepads.

00:19:33.860 --> 00:19:35.940
All of these combine for
a fantastic living room

00:19:35.940 --> 00:19:38.190
experience, and we can't
wait to see the growth

00:19:38.190 --> 00:19:39.970
and what you bring
to Android TV.

00:19:39.970 --> 00:19:41.910
But we also have a
goal of actually making

00:19:41.910 --> 00:19:44.260
the gaming experience more
dynamic in the living room.

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:46.120
This is especially
in a world where,

00:19:46.120 --> 00:19:49.060
from my own personal point
of view-- local multiplayer

00:19:49.060 --> 00:19:50.954
and second screen experiences.

00:19:50.954 --> 00:19:52.620
And so today, we're
announcing something

00:19:52.620 --> 00:19:55.800
that we call the
Nearby Connections API.

00:19:55.800 --> 00:19:58.310
With this new protocol,
games can seamlessly

00:19:58.310 --> 00:20:01.180
connect smartphones
and tablets to games

00:20:01.180 --> 00:20:03.220
on the TV in front of them.

00:20:03.220 --> 00:20:05.280
